  "prompt": "What are the differences between lumped and distributed networks?",
  "response": "Let me explain the key differences between lumped and distributed networks:\n\nLumped Networks:\n1. Discrete components\n2. Ideal components with zero internal resistance\n3. Typically used at low frequencies\n4. Components considered point-like\n5. Negligible propagation delays\n6. Uniform properties throughout network\n7. Simple circuit analysis techniques\n8. Examples: RC, LC circuits\n9. Ideal assumptions about component behavior\n\nDistributed Networks:\n1. Continuous physical structures\n2. Real components with internal resistance\n3. Used at high frequencies\n4. Components have spatial distribution\n5. Significant propagation delays\n6. Varying properties across network\n7. Complex wave propagation analysis\n8. Examples: transmission lines, waveguides\n9. Considers electromagnetic wave characteristics\n10. Includes transmission line effects\n11. Requires distributed parameter models\n12. More accurate representation of real-world systems\n\nKey distinguishing factors include frequency, component complexity, signal propagation, and modeling approach. The choice depends on specific application requirements and signal characteristics.",
